ame of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Curteis was born about 1330, in Hanbury, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of William Curteis. She had at least 5 sons with William Burton. She died about 1391, in Tutbury, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 63."},"et":{"Abt 1330–Abt 1391":"umbes 1330–umbes 1391","1330–1391":"1330–1391","1327–1382":"1327–1382","1361–1420":"1361–1420","1361–1466":"1361–1466","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","1368–1461":"1368–1461","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1330":"1330","1461":"1461","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","Abt 1368":"umbes 1368","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","Abt 1362":"umbes 1362","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","Abt 1382":"umbes 1382","1368":"1368","1466":"1466","1420":"1420","Abt 1330":"umbes 1330","Abt 1391":"umbes 1391","Hanbury, Staffordshire, England":"Hanbury, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tutbury, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom